        <h1 className="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 dark:text-white mb-4 tracking-tight">
          Income <span className="text-blue-500">Tax Calculator</span>
        </h1>
        <p className="text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
          Stop guessing your tax burden. Calculate your exact take-home pay, apply deductions, and see your net monthly income instantly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <Suspense fallback={<div className="h-96 animate-pulse bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-800 rounded-3xl w-full"></div>}>
        <IncomeTaxClient />
      </Suspense>

      <ToolArticle title="Mastering Your Paycheck: How Taxes Work">
        <p>
          Understanding your paycheck is the first step to financial literacy. When you negotiate a salary with an employer, you agree on a <strong>Gross Income</strong>. However, the amount that actually hits your bank account every month—your <strong>Net Income</strong>—is significantly lower. This calculator helps bridge that gap so you can budget accurately.
        </p>

        <h3>Taxable Income vs. Gross Income</h3>
        <p>
          The government does not tax your entire Gross Income. Before taxes are calculated, you are allowed to subtract certain expenses, known as <strong>Deductions</strong>. 
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Standard Deduction:</strong> A flat amount the government allows everyone to deduct from their income to cover basic living expenses.</li>
          <li><strong>Itemized Deductions:</strong> Specific expenses you can deduct instead of the standard deduction, such as mortgage interest, charitable donations, and medical expenses.</li>
          <li><strong>Pre-tax Contributions:</strong> Money you put into health insurance premiums or retirement accounts (like a 401k or IRA) is often deducted from your paycheck before taxes are applied.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Your Gross Income minus your Deductions equals your <strong>Taxable Income</strong>. This is the number the government uses to calculate how much tax you owe.</p>

        <h3>Marginal vs. Effective Tax Rates</h3>
        <p>
          Most tax systems are progressive, meaning your income is broken up into "brackets," and each bracket is taxed at a different rate. 
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, your first $10,000 might be taxed at 10%, and your next $30,000 might be taxed at 12%. If you earn $40,000, your <em>Marginal Tax Rate</em> (the highest bracket you fell into) is 12%. However, your <em>Effective Tax Rate</em> (the average percentage you paid across all brackets) will be lower than 12%. When using this calculator, you should enter your estimated Effective Tax Rate for the most accurate results.
        </p>
      </ToolArticle>

      <FAQAccordion items={faqs} />
    </div>
